00:01:45.860 --> 00:01:48.360
but often they don't have the context

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:52.360
that they need to do the work that you need reliably.

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:57.160
So for example, if you are asking it to follow a workflow,

00:01:57.160 --> 00:01:59.540
if you're asking it to create slides

00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:01.839
and you find yourself repeatedly being like,

00:02:01.839 --> 00:02:04.820
hey, please use these specific packages,

00:02:04.820 --> 00:02:07.440
or hey, use these brand guidelines

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:10.759
every single time you give it a prompt,

00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:15.000
that is when you may want to consider using skills.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.919
That's the kind of friction that skills were built to solve.

00:02:18.919 --> 00:02:21.679
So instead of opening a new project

00:02:21.679 --> 00:02:24.479
and copying, pasting the same block

00:02:24.479 --> 00:02:28.279
of organizational rules that you have,

00:02:28.279 --> 00:02:32.279
which works, but can be tedious and error prone,

00:02:32.279 --> 00:02:34.160
very easy to forget,

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:36.399
you can solve this by packaging

00:02:36.399 --> 00:02:38.720
all of your procedural knowledge

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:41.360
and things like your company, your team,

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:43.600
your user specific context

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:48.179
into portable version controlled folders and files

00:02:48.179 --> 00:02:52.100
that then your coding assistant can load on demand.

00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:54.339
And my colleague, Gary Caden Bowie,

00:02:54.339 --> 00:02:57.100
who's a developer here at Posit,

00:02:57.100 --> 00:02:58.820
has said, if you find yourself

00:02:58.820 --> 00:03:00.619
saying the same thing to a model,

00:03:00.619 --> 00:03:03.339
it's a great moment to stop and make a skill.

00:03:06.179 --> 00:03:08.100
In terms of what skills are,

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:11.460
at their core skills are Markdown files,

00:03:11.460 --> 00:03:15.259
and Markdown is a lightweight markup language

00:03:15.259 --> 00:03:17.220
with plain text formatting.

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:20.179
If you've ever used R Markdown or Quarto,

00:03:20.179 --> 00:03:22.339
you have used Markdown.

00:03:22.339 --> 00:03:24.979
And these files live in a folder

00:03:24.979 --> 00:03:27.539
that your coding assistant can find.

00:03:27.539 --> 00:03:30.539
And many, many coding assistants

00:03:30.539 --> 00:03:34.100
follow the specifications for skills.

00:03:34.100 --> 00:03:35.580
And so they know where to look

00:03:35.580 --> 00:03:38.779
and what to do when they find these files.

00:03:38.779 --> 00:03:43.179
And even though I mentioned coding assistants specifically,

00:03:43.179 --> 00:03:46.500
skills are actually supported in other sorts of programs.

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:50.339
If you use Cloud Cowork, which is a desktop app,

00:03:50.339 --> 00:03:52.660
those actually support skills as well.

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:54.740
But just in the context of today

00:03:54.740 --> 00:03:57.380
and this conference and us as you are users,

00:03:57.380 --> 00:04:00.619
I'm going to be focusing specific on coding assistants

00:04:00.619 --> 00:04:03.820
like Posit Assistant and Cloud Code.

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:06.979
And so in terms of these files and folders,

00:04:06.979 --> 00:04:08.899
they can live globally.

00:04:08.899 --> 00:04:12.339
And so this means that every time

00:04:12.339 --> 00:04:15.220
that you go to work with your coding assistant,

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:18.700
it'll be there installed and ready to go.

00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:22.739
And skills can also be installed at a project level.

00:04:22.739 --> 00:04:26.100
So if you need a specific skill for a specific project,

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:27.579
you could do that as well.

00:04:27.579 --> 00:04:30.459
And it won't be available to every single project

00:04:30.459 --> 00:04:31.540
that you open up.

00:04:35.579 --> 00:04:38.579
And so here's an example of what that looks like.

00:04:38.579 --> 00:04:42.820
So if you imagine the left-hand side is my file explorer,

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:47.380
I have a project open where I have a .cloud folder,

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:49.260
within that, a skills folder,

00:04:49.260 --> 00:04:51.779
within that, a shinybslib folder,

00:04:51.779 --> 00:04:54.260
and then within that, a skill.nd,

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:57.579
that markdown file that defines a skill.

00:04:57.579 --> 00:05:00.779
And because it's a markdown file, like a readme file,

00:05:00.779 --> 00:05:02.899
you can click that and open it up

00:05:02.899 --> 00:05:06.459
and take a look at what is inside.

00:05:06.459 --> 00:05:09.059
And in terms of the anatomy of a skill,

00:05:09.299 --> 00:05:12.980
what actually defines a skill in this markdown file?

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:17.980
So if you have used Cordo or R Markdown before,

00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:21.619
you may be familiar with this YAML header.

00:05:21.619 --> 00:05:24.899
So it's denoted by three dashes.

00:05:24.899 --> 00:05:27.500
And then inside those three dashes,

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:29.779
there is a key value pair.

00:05:29.779 --> 00:05:32.459
So the key in this case would be name.

00:05:32.459 --> 00:05:36.059
The value is shinybslib.

00:05:36.059 --> 00:05:41.059
And so the first required piece of a skill is this name,

00:05:42.859 --> 00:05:45.339
which must also match the folder name

00:05:45.339 --> 00:05:47.140
in which it is contained.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:48.899
That's how the assistant knows

00:05:48.899 --> 00:05:51.260
to actually go ahead and find it.

00:05:52.339 --> 00:05:55.019
And then second is the description,

00:05:55.019 --> 00:05:58.260
which is probably the most important field.

00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:00.980
I think this can be a little bit misleading

00:06:00.980 --> 00:06:03.260
because it sounds like, oh, a description.

00:06:03.299 --> 00:06:06.380
I just need to write out what exactly this,

00:06:06.380 --> 00:06:08.899
what description of the skill.

00:06:08.899 --> 00:06:13.420
But in fact, this skill is how the model decides

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:16.339
whether or not to load the full skill.

00:06:16.339 --> 00:06:20.339
It'll read this, it'll search for keywords and context,

00:06:20.339 --> 00:06:23.100
and then decide yes or no in terms of,

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:25.779
yes, I'm going to use this skill.

00:06:25.779 --> 00:06:27.899
And so even though it sounds like

00:06:27.899 --> 00:06:29.739
it's a description for humans,

00:06:29.739 --> 00:06:32.579
it's in fact a description for the model.

00:06:32.579 --> 00:06:35.339
And so it's very important to know,

00:06:37.019 --> 00:06:39.260
or to write a very good description

00:06:39.260 --> 00:06:42.380
so that your skill is loaded appropriately.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:48.579
And then below the YAML header is your actual content.

00:06:48.579 --> 00:06:52.220
So these are the instructions and the worked examples,

00:06:52.220 --> 00:06:56.220
the guardrails, whatever you want your model to do

00:06:56.220 --> 00:06:58.179
whenever you give it a command.

00:06:58.899 --> 00:07:01.100
And in terms of how it works,

00:07:01.100 --> 00:07:03.820
the coding assistant would load skills

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:07.299
through something that's called progressive disclosure.

00:07:07.299 --> 00:07:10.660
It doesn't load every single skill up front.

00:07:10.660 --> 00:07:13.299
Instead, it keeps a lightweight index

00:07:13.299 --> 00:07:15.660
of just those names and descriptions.

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:19.220
And at startup, that's all that it reads.

00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:23.859
Then you give the coding agent a command,

00:07:23.859 --> 00:07:26.500
like, hey, build me a BSLib dash.

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:29.579
Hey, build me a BSLib dashboard.

00:07:29.579 --> 00:07:33.299
At this point, this is when the agent would,

00:07:33.299 --> 00:07:36.899
or the coding assistant would scan all those descriptions

00:07:36.899 --> 00:07:39.619
and then again, look for those keywords and be like,

00:07:39.619 --> 00:07:41.339
hey, does this match the command

00:07:41.339 --> 00:07:44.100
that I was just given or not?

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:46.739
And again, this is meant to be just enough

00:07:46.739 --> 00:07:50.220
to know whether or not the skill is relevant.

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:54.700
And only then, if it assesses, yes,

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:56.220
this skill is relevant,

00:07:56.220 --> 00:08:00.940
will the coding assistant read in the full skill MD file.

00:08:00.940 --> 00:08:02.420
And then at this point,

00:08:02.420 --> 00:08:05.579
the coding assistant follows the different instructions

00:08:06.540 --> 00:08:09.980
based on whatever is specified

00:08:09.980 --> 00:08:12.299
in the actual body of the skill.

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:18.299
And you may have heard of something called agent.md

00:08:18.299 --> 00:08:20.579
or claw.md.

00:08:20.579 --> 00:08:23.940
And so agent is more general,

00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:28.059
claw.md is specific for clawed code.

00:08:28.059 --> 00:08:31.019
And there are a lot of similarities.

00:08:31.019 --> 00:08:34.700
Clawed or agent.md are also markdown files

00:08:34.700 --> 00:08:37.619
with instructions for your model

00:08:37.619 --> 00:08:41.500
and your coding assistant in terms of telling it what to do.

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:46.500
However, one issue of putting everything within claw.md

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:49.940
is this idea of context limits.

00:08:49.940 --> 00:08:53.619
So your model can only hold so much information

00:08:53.619 --> 00:08:55.500
at a particular time.

00:08:55.500 --> 00:08:59.299
And if your agent.md file is really, really big,

00:08:59.299 --> 00:09:03.219
it's going to hit its context limit really fast.

00:09:03.219 --> 00:09:05.979
And the issue with that is as you add on

00:09:05.979 --> 00:09:07.700
more and more instructions,

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:10.500
your model doesn't actually necessarily get better.

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:11.940
They can get worse.

00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:14.500
They can start to drift.

00:09:14.500 --> 00:09:16.940
They forget the rules that you gave it.

00:09:16.940 --> 00:09:19.460
It starts to hallucinate and so on.

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:22.140
And then of course, as a user,

00:09:22.140 --> 00:09:27.020
what this means is every time you are opening up a project,

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:29.099
your agent.md file is read,

00:09:29.099 --> 00:09:33.140
you're using more tokens than you absolutely need,

00:09:33.140 --> 00:09:35.820
which can incur further costs from you.

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:39.539
Versus a catalog of skills,

00:09:39.539 --> 00:09:43.219
which are again focused and it avoids this issue

00:09:43.219 --> 00:09:47.979
by having sort of a playlist only for the task at hand.

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:50.099
They're small and composable,

00:09:50.099 --> 00:09:54.020
and you can just pick them out as you need them.

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:56.979
So you and the model are really only paying

00:09:56.979 --> 00:09:59.659
for what you're actually going to be using.

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:04.419
In terms of say you have your collection of skills,

00:10:04.419 --> 00:10:07.940
how do you actually invoke or use your skills?

00:10:07.940 --> 00:10:09.940
There's two different ways.

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:11.900
One way is explicitly.

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:14.619
So you can use what's called a slash command.

00:10:14.619 --> 00:10:17.700
So a forward slash and then the name of the skill

00:10:18.380 --> 00:10:19.380
to call the skill by name.

00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:21.780
And you could do this if you say no,

00:10:21.780 --> 00:10:26.059
that you're going to be creating a BS Lib app,

00:10:27.419 --> 00:10:30.460
but more likely you will be doing it automatically.

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:33.500
So when you say, hey, build me a dashboard

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:35.380
for so-and-so thing,

00:10:35.380 --> 00:10:38.539
it's going to read those names and descriptions.

00:10:38.539 --> 00:10:41.979
Again, based on it's like a small index,

00:10:41.979 --> 00:10:44.780
it's going to determine based on the context,

00:10:44.780 --> 00:10:46.700
whether or not the skill is relevant.

00:10:46.739 --> 00:10:49.979
And I'll let you know, hey, the skill is loaded.

00:10:49.979 --> 00:10:53.659
You know, in this case, Shiny BS Lib has been loaded.

00:10:53.659 --> 00:10:57.500
And so again, it only works as well as your description,

00:10:57.500 --> 00:11:00.539
which is another reason to spend a little bit of time

00:11:00.539 --> 00:11:01.580
on that field.

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:06.739
So I wanted to show a really quick example

00:11:06.739 --> 00:11:08.940
of what this actually looks like.

00:11:08.940 --> 00:11:12.380
I do ask for your grace at being a life coding

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:14.419
and then also LLNs.

00:11:14.419 --> 00:11:16.580
You never know what it's going to do,

