00:15:33.299 --> 00:15:38.299
So there is a command from Versa Labs called NPX skills,

00:15:39.219 --> 00:15:40.820
which you can run in the terminal.

00:15:40.820 --> 00:15:42.900
And it's really nice because it gives you

00:15:42.900 --> 00:15:44.219
an interactive picker

00:15:44.219 --> 00:15:47.059
for all of these different community skills.

00:15:47.059 --> 00:15:49.179
There are also a lot of different advantages

00:15:49.179 --> 00:15:51.659
for installing it this way

00:15:51.659 --> 00:15:55.059
because this directory also adds some metadata

00:15:55.059 --> 00:15:57.140
so that you can keep track of your skill

00:15:57.140 --> 00:16:00.140
and see where did you download this and so on.

00:16:00.140 --> 00:16:02.859
And then it also has things like security features

00:16:02.859 --> 00:16:05.380
because you are installing instructions

00:16:05.380 --> 00:16:07.340
from another source.

00:16:08.900 --> 00:16:12.140
You can also just pass your coding assistant a URL

00:16:12.140 --> 00:16:14.380
and say, hey, make a skill from this.

00:16:15.619 --> 00:16:18.859
So like if a skill already exists and you give it a URL,

00:16:18.859 --> 00:16:22.020
I'll put it in the correct folder and so on.

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:25.460
In addition, if you just have the file,

00:16:25.460 --> 00:16:27.859
say as a downloadable file,

00:16:27.859 --> 00:16:31.179
you can just plop it into your coding assistant

00:16:31.179 --> 00:16:33.219
and have it create the skill for you.

00:16:35.020 --> 00:16:38.059
Or because again, everything is living

00:16:38.059 --> 00:16:41.059
either in your global directory or your project directory,

00:16:41.059 --> 00:16:42.099
if you have that file,

00:16:42.099 --> 00:16:45.739
you can drag it and drop it into that folder yourself.

00:16:45.739 --> 00:16:49.539
And if you're working in R, there's a package called BTW,

00:16:49.539 --> 00:16:52.539
which has helper functions for installing skills

00:16:52.539 --> 00:16:55.500
from GitHub or R packages.

00:16:57.340 --> 00:16:59.820
And if you want to create a brand new skill,

00:16:59.859 --> 00:17:02.020
you don't have to write a skill from scratch.

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:03.500
In fact, you probably shouldn't.

00:17:03.500 --> 00:17:07.099
There are skills whose entire jobs are to write skills.

00:17:07.099 --> 00:17:08.939
And so in Posit Assistant,

00:17:08.939 --> 00:17:11.300
you would write the slash create skill

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:14.099
or cloud code slash skill creator

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:17.819
or from BTW, BTW task create skill.

00:17:17.819 --> 00:17:19.540
And then from here,

00:17:19.540 --> 00:17:21.819
you would describe what the skill would do

00:17:21.819 --> 00:17:23.699
and the assistant will scaffold

00:17:23.699 --> 00:17:26.900
the skill.md file for you.

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:31.900
AgentSkills.io is like the definitive guide

00:17:31.900 --> 00:17:33.900
for the skill specification.

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:36.900
And they actually have a lot of great best practices.

00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:39.099
So in terms of how to create a new skill,

00:17:39.099 --> 00:17:42.420
they recommend including domain specific knowledge,

00:17:42.420 --> 00:17:45.300
being really specific in terms of your patterns,

00:17:45.300 --> 00:17:47.780
your edge cases, your conventions,

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:50.219
and then working through a real task

00:17:50.219 --> 00:17:53.420
and then extracting it into a reusable skill

00:17:53.420 --> 00:17:55.180
rather than trying to work with

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:56.739
kind of like vague definitions

00:17:56.739 --> 00:17:59.180
and build a skill from there.

00:17:59.180 --> 00:18:01.979
So definitely check out their website if you have a chance.

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:06.380
And this is a topic that I would love to hear

00:18:06.380 --> 00:18:09.500
from everybody in terms of if you are using skills,

00:18:09.500 --> 00:18:11.579
how do you manage or organize them?

00:18:11.579 --> 00:18:13.099
Because as you imagine,

00:18:13.099 --> 00:18:17.500
as your collection of skills start to grow,

00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:20.020
organization seems would matter more

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:22.579
for you to remember like what exactly do I have

00:18:23.420 --> 00:18:26.579
and how does everything kind of relate to each other?

00:18:26.579 --> 00:18:30.099
And two examples of managing skills that I have found

00:18:30.099 --> 00:18:32.260
is asking your coding assistant

00:18:32.260 --> 00:18:34.780
to help you create a generic meta skill

00:18:34.780 --> 00:18:38.020
whose entire job is just wrangling your other skills.

00:18:38.020 --> 00:18:40.099
And then another one is grouping skills

00:18:40.099 --> 00:18:42.660
into subfolders within your skills directory.

00:18:42.660 --> 00:18:45.819
So that way, only the skills related to Pharma

00:18:45.819 --> 00:18:48.420
get pulled in, only to Shiny get pulled in

00:18:48.420 --> 00:18:50.819
and you can see them all in a single place.

00:18:52.979 --> 00:18:54.260
There are times that skills

00:18:54.260 --> 00:18:56.060
are not the right tools for the job.

00:18:56.060 --> 00:18:58.579
So if you have a lot of live changing data,

00:18:58.579 --> 00:19:01.619
you might wanna consider a model context protocol.

00:19:01.619 --> 00:19:04.619
There are lots of talks today too that mention MCPs.

00:19:04.619 --> 00:19:05.780
So definitely check them out

00:19:05.780 --> 00:19:08.260
to see how they contrast with skills.

00:19:08.260 --> 00:19:10.660
If you have a pile of documents,

00:19:10.660 --> 00:19:14.900
you wanna do retrieval augmented generation or RAG instead.

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:17.500
But if what you're focused on is repeatable,

00:19:17.500 --> 00:19:20.939
know-how procedure, that's when you want to use skills.

00:19:22.660 --> 00:19:26.099
And I mentioned earlier, skills are markdown files.

00:19:26.099 --> 00:19:28.459
That's a bit of a simplification.

00:19:28.459 --> 00:19:31.099
They can actually contain a lot of other things

00:19:31.099 --> 00:19:32.780
like scripts and references.

00:19:32.780 --> 00:19:33.900
I'm almost done, Bill.

00:19:35.459 --> 00:19:37.500
Here are a few places where to find skills.

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:39.819
And as Bill mentioned, the very next talk

00:19:39.819 --> 00:19:42.579
is going to talk about a collection of skills

00:19:42.579 --> 00:19:43.739
that you could start using

00:19:43.739 --> 00:19:45.619
and picking up for your Pharma work.

00:19:46.579 --> 00:19:49.099
And then here are a few other talks

00:19:49.099 --> 00:19:51.060
that specifically mention skills.

00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:52.579
At this very conference today

00:19:52.579 --> 00:19:54.979
that you should definitely go check out.

00:19:54.979 --> 00:19:59.500
And finally, here is the app that Cloud Code created.

00:19:59.500 --> 00:20:02.339
And as you can see here, BS Lib is right at the top.

00:20:04.219 --> 00:20:06.260
And with that, thank you.

00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:08.099
Awesome.

00:20:08.099 --> 00:20:09.939
Isabella, we've got a couple of quick questions.

00:20:09.939 --> 00:20:11.380
I think there's three or four in the chat.

00:20:11.380 --> 00:20:12.219
I'm gonna leave those to you.

00:20:12.219 --> 00:20:13.579
I've got one quick one though.

00:20:13.579 --> 00:20:16.300
I thought we could just answer here.

00:20:16.300 --> 00:20:17.739
What's the difference would you say

00:20:18.020 --> 00:20:21.619
between a skill and a tool call or an MCP

00:20:21.619 --> 00:20:24.380
for someone new to skills?

00:20:24.380 --> 00:20:25.219
Yeah, yeah.

00:20:25.219 --> 00:20:28.979
So I'm sorry that I had to go over it so fast,

00:20:28.979 --> 00:20:31.500
but skills is more on what to do,

00:20:31.500 --> 00:20:33.699
like these kinds of procedures and things like that.

00:20:33.699 --> 00:20:36.380
But if you have, if you need to require access

00:20:36.380 --> 00:20:40.099
to real life data, that's constantly changing, right?

00:20:40.099 --> 00:20:43.540
That's when you want to consider an MCP instead.

00:20:43.540 --> 00:20:47.060
And so both tools for Gen AI,

00:20:47.060 --> 00:20:50.540
but they have slightly different focuses.

